metadata.name: ZOOM (4hwf) #17
metadata.description:
"Das System lässt keine Überraschung zu. Überraschung ist Ausdruck partieller Unkenntnis. Überraschung weist auf Mangel von Wissen hin, deutet Leerstellen an. Bisher hatten sie keine Leerstellen festgestellt." — Herbert W. Franke

ZOOM explores linear scaling of pixels by zooming into a noisy framebuffer. Various zoom levels are composed one below the other, becoming a cinematic animation through iteration of the hue values of the pixels in the framebuffer.

In Gedenken an Herbert W. Franke
Kim Asendorf, 2022

metadata.name: Sugar Skulls #48
metadata.description:
Sugar Skulls are confectionery creations traditionally made with cane sugar and decorated as part of the Mexican celebration of Day of the Dead, or Día de Muertos and All Souls Day on the first and second days of November when the dead are remembered and honored. 

So, why are they showing up here at Christmas? Well, why not?!? Christmas is a great time to enjoy a free, sweet treat while remembering those loved ones we’ve spent past Christmases with who are no longer with us.  

While most images here are of traditional sugar skulls, some lucky ones are accessorized with Santa Claus or Elf hats. 

Minting is free for as long as the project remains open. The creator may elect to close the project at any time. There is absolutely no utility promised or implied beyond the nifty artwork itself. Created for Christmas 2022.

Merry Christmas!

metadata.name: THE GRID #48
metadata.description: This is THE GRID, it's composed of small generative tiles assembled in an organised chaos. Everything you see is generated live, the shapes, the camera/lens, colors are also procedural (not based on predefined palettes). Be sure to use the variation button to see what it can do.

metadata.name: Clutch #248
metadata.description:
Halftones, dynamic composition and high color contrasts for a groovy composition inspired by action b-movies, their posters and music.

Semi-realtime javascript / webgl.
Desktop / Chrome recommended.

You can find more infos about the project in the fx(text) linked below.

Controls :
- Press [SPACE] to show/hide the user interface
- Mouse wheel/middle/ Pinch : Zoom
- After zooming, Mouse left / Drag : Pan

Keyboard shortcuts and additionnal instructions : 
- [R]eset the camera.
- Toggle the [F]rame.
- Unlock the [C]amera, with rotation on Mouse2.
- Export a PNG capture at various resolutions by pressing the number keys [1] to [9] (top row or numpad, and only in live mode, after pressing "open"). I recommend starting with [4] and going from there. What is captured is what's on screen, so you can get creative if you so desire.

NFT License

metadata.name: f-emerald #224
metadata.description:
f-emerald generates unique ephemeral crystal-like structures that morph in space. each generation has a different shape, animation and colour palette. 

the crystals flicker with colours in the dark most of the time. there is, however, a 20% chance of obtaining a crystal on a bright background with a light colour palette and one out of ten structures is created in black and white.

metadata.name: fx(haish) / the Generator #363
metadata.description:
fx(haish) is my contribution to #fxhashturnsone
fx(haish) is not a finished product
fx(haish) is a co-creation experiment
fx(haish) is a fun exploration of a mixed GenAI process

fx(haish) is my Happy Birthday to fx(hash). 

Have fun, collectors!


// HOW TO PARTICIPATE

Step 1. Mint or collect “fx(haish) - the Generator”
Step 2. Visit https://www.arqtistic.com/fx(haish) to generate your “fx(haish) - The AI City” based on your mint. You have 20 tries.
Step 3. Await further instructions.


// FURTHER INFO

This algorithm has been designed to produce images which are suitable for the subsequent AI generation. The token consists of a random number of randomly placed and sized rectangles, filled with a noise gradient pattern. In short, Diffusion AI Models thrive on noise.

The AI generation uses Stable Diffusion 1.5 through an API designed by the 330ai team (@Pixelmindai). The WebUI has been developed by Nik0gda (@AntonCebanu2). AI Prompt has been designed (by me) to produce images of Cities, but you can possibly make it do other things, if you try hard enough.

metadata.name: fx(splash) #312
metadata.description:
To celebrate fx(hash) turning 1 year old I've created this token as a part of the #fxhashturnsone event! It's a playful and colorful token symbolizing the experiences I've had with this platform.


The piece uses shaders to generate it's visuals which means that outputs will vary from device to device, and the preview might not look the exact same as your live view.

For that same reason I do not recommend running this piece on a mobile device as the shaders can be quite heavy and blurry on lower-tier hardware. My recommended way of viewing this token is on a pc.


--

To open the export menu double click the screen. Here you can export in a multitude of resolutions.

--


50% of primary proceeds will be donated to the processing foundation, learn more about them here:
https://processingfoundation.org

Made with opengl shaders and p5js by WootScoot, 2022.

metadata.name: Gerhard #63
metadata.description:
Gerhard is a collaboration of Richard Nadler and Leander Herzog on fxhash. A generative animation based on multiple layers of color and data, mixed, moved and painted over in realtime. Some fragments stick to the canvas while others get discarded to leave the existing layers visible, allowing a complex surface to emerge and build up over time. 
Richard Nadler created the textures to control composition and color. Leander Herzog created the code for the interplay between the layers, motion and interactions. Both artists use different tools and are not aware of the details of each others process, meeting through the interface of pixels. This collaboration is enabled by twitter and fxhash, as the generative art community continues to explore abstraction in summer 2022 – while extreme temperatures, wildfires, ongoing conflicts and volatile markets continue to escalate. 

- Click to start a new layer of motion and color. 
- Doubleclick to enter fullscreen mode. 
- Press “s” to save the current canvas. 
- Append ?dpr=4 to the url to increase the resolution.

https://leanderherzog.ch/2022/gerhard/

metadata.name: The Face We Had #97
metadata.description:
The Face We Had is a series of generative, moving sculptures attempting to express the artists personal thoughts, experiences and inclinations related to meditative and altered states of consciousness. In a non-descriptive way, the piece aims to reflect the always changing nature of mind through patterns of movement and assemblages of form, color and organic shapes, endlessly revolving around a perceived point of origin.  

Although not intended as literal depictions, the elements interact in a way that could be interpreted as dance-like interactions between thought patterns, mental energy, feelings, fragments of memories and layers of personal identity. 



Interactive features:

space - pause/play
w - wireframe view
d - debug view (compute textures)
s - save screenshot

metadata.name: The Slow Climb #39
metadata.description:
The quickest path to the top can be seen only after reaching the top. Following any other path, no doubt will take longer and will be more difficult.

The path you chose to take may not be straight, it may be full of obstacles, it may even seem impossible to continue at times. Add to that, you have no idea how long more it will take. It is also possible that this path may not lead you to the top.

What is certain is that if you stop climbing just now, you will never reach the top.

So, will you keep climbing or stop and go back?

* * *

S: Save PNG
D: Hide dents

To save a larger image, open live view, add "&s=WIDTH_IN_PIXELS" to the end of the URL, press Enter and then press S.

Chrome is recommended for faster rendering.

Artwork by: yenren / twitter.com/yenrenART
License: NFT License 2.0 / CC BY-NC-ND 4.0

metadata.name: Primordial #164
metadata.description:
Primordial is a study of abstract forms. The algorithm, written in p5.js and WebGL, utilizes domain warping to create twisted fields of color and then overlays thousands of tiny lines to provide depth and texture. The outputs are chaotic but not completely formless, like a swirling mass of plasma from the early universe, or a strange proto-life form suspended in prehistoric ooze.

CONTROLS:

1-9: Increase resolution and save image in PNG format

B: Toggle borders on/off

F: Fullscreen
P: Portrait
L: Landscape
S: Square

For third party license information, please see license.md

David Brice Allen
October 2022

This project is being released in celebration of the 1 year aniversary of Achromat, my first release on fxhash. In addition to being inspired by Achromat, aspects of other previous projects have been incorporated. My deepest gratitude to all who have collected my work over the past year.
